<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[707,1194,1257,1729]" lastBlockId="3.[685,1173,194,1729]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,836,1522,1543]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Together these are the only 
<collectingRegion box="[1093,1193,1549,1570]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">California</collectingRegion>
<taxonomicName authorityName="MARSEUL" authorityYear="1853" box="[707,841,1576,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[707,841,1576,1597]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Margarinotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibiting a single lateral pronotal stria (the outer stria being completely absent; 
<figureCitation box="[707,783,1629,1650]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[197,229,1171,1190]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,183,1148]" captionTargetId="figure-217@2.[173,1193,183,1148]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Margarinotus ephemeralis. A. Frons, anterior view. B. Elytron, dorsal view. C. Pronotum, dorsal view. D. Pygidium, posterodorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892930" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892930/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Externally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caterino" authorityYear="2010" box="[919,1072,1629,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[919,1072,1629,1650]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">M. ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can usually be separated by the pronotal punctation, where it has irregular punctures mediad of the apical half to two-thirds of the inner pronotal stria, this group of punctures approximately as wide as the space between the pronotal margin and lateral stria. These are both denser and occupy slightly more space than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[278,383,862,883]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[278,383,862,883]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It has an additional cluster of pronotal punctures on each side just behind the anterior stria, approximately posterad eye, which is very inconspicuous or lacking in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[465,572,942,963]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[465,572,942,963]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the male, in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[354,429,969,990]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), the apical half of the median lobe of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caterino" authorityYear="2010" box="[304,453,995,1016]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[304,453,995,1016]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is narrower, and is markedly narrowed in the apical one-fifth in partic- ular, whereas that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[888,997,194,215]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[888,997,194,215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is broader, flatter, and narrowed just at the apex. The apex of the median lobe bears a simple dorsal process in both species, but that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[872,981,274,295]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[872,981,274,295]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is low and rounded (in apical view; 
<figureCitation box="[836,909,300,321]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) and that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caterino" authorityYear="2010" box="[1026,1171,300,321]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[1026,1171,300,321]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more strongly elevated and subquadrate (
<figureCitation box="[1088,1161,327,348]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). The median armature is quite different in the two, with the arms of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. L. LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[843,949,380,401]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[843,949,380,401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
thin, acute, and slightly dorsally curved (
<figureCitation box="[865,985,406,428]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs. 2E–F</figureCitation>
). The arms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caterino" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Margarinotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">M. ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more nearly triangular, straighter along the leading edge, and straight to subserrate along the trailing edge, with the apices less strongly pointed (
<figureCitation box="[771,885,512,534]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[175,207,596,615]" captionTargetBox="[166,636,203,554]" captionTargetId="figure-550@3.[151,638,183,572]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Margarinotus ephemeralis and Margarinotus remotus, median lobe of aedeagus. A. M. ephemeralis, dorsal view.B.M. ephemeralis, lateral view.C. M. ephemeralis, apical view of gonopore. D. M. remotus, apical view of gonopore. E. M. remotus, dorsal view. F. M. remotus, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4892934" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4892934/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs. 2A–B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
